    {
        "content": "<p>Explanation of the declarations diff: <a class=\"message-link\" href=\"/#narrow/channel/144837-PR-reviews/topic/.2319115.20Generalize.20flatness.20to.20semirings/near/493944787\">#PR reviews &gt; #19115 Generalize flatness to semirings @ ðŸ’¬</a></p>",
        "id": 493944598,
        "sender_full_name": "Junyan Xu",
        "timestamp": 1736952549
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><a href=\"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/pull/20774\">#20774</a> makes mathlib slightly faster, though the speedups in CardinalEmb and RelRank are due to AddCommMonoid instance reminders within proofs.</p>",
        "id": 493961987,
        "sender_full_name": "Junyan Xu",
        "timestamp": 1736957164
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>It turns out the \"flatness\" in <a href=\"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/pull/19115\">#19115</a> is called \"mono-flatness\" in the <a href=\"https://link.springer.com/content/pdf/10.1007/s00012-004-1865-1.pdf\">literature</a>. The difference is that tensoring with a mono-flat module preserves monomorphisms, while tensoring with a flat module preserves all finite limits. (Modules over semirings are called \"semimodules\" in the literature.)</p>",
        "id": 494008649,
        "sender_full_name": "Junyan Xu",
        "timestamp": 1736972334
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>It turns out a professor (Markus Banagl) in my university (Heidelberg) <a href=\"https://www.mathi.uni-heidelberg.de/~banagl/pdfdocs/TensorSemimod.pdf\">publishes about semimodules</a>, and it's used in TQFT ...<br>\nThe paper says the semimodule tensor product (same as in mathlib) was constructed by Y. Katsov in 1997. Should we add a reference to that paper?</p>",
        "id": 494008940,
        "sender_full_name": "Junyan Xu",
        "timestamp": 1736972445
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><a href=\"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/pull/23742\">#23742</a> is a case where an attempt to generalize to semirings led me to discover a proof that golfed 100 lines away from Mathlib. The mathematical lesson is posted in <a href=\"https://stacks.math.columbia.edu/tag/00FK#comment-10079\">this comment on Stacks Project</a>.</p>",
        "id": 510727886,
        "sender_full_name": "Junyan Xu",
        "timestamp": 1744046569
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Isn't it the same proof? Just avoiding localization and quotient by talking of the ideals themselves?</p>",
        "id": 510854344,
        "sender_full_name": "Antoine Chambert-Loir",
        "timestamp": 1744096052
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"224323\">Junyan Xu</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/116395-maths/topic/Linear.20independence.20over.20semirings/near/487056271\">said</a>:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kn\">import</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Mathlib</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">RingTheory</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">IsTensorProduct</span>\n<span class=\"kn\">variable</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">{</span><span class=\"n\">R</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">S</span><span class=\"o\">}</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">CommSemiring</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">R</span><span class=\"o\">]</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">CommRing</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">S</span><span class=\"o\">]</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">Algebra</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">R</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">S</span><span class=\"o\">]</span>\n<span class=\"kn\">example</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Algebra</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">IsPushout</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">â„•</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">â„¤</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">R</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">S</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">â†”</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"bp\">âˆƒ</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">f</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"bp\">âŠ¤</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">AddSubmonoid</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">R</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">LocalizationMap</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">S</span><span class=\"o\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">f</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">toFun</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">algebraMap</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">R</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">S</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"gr\">sorry</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>I now have this <a href=\"https://github.com/alreadydone/mathlib4/blob/7500f0e36377c3250a328321d13932315908cf09/Mathlib/RingTheory/Localization/Additive.lean#L457-L458\">in #28468</a> stated using an extracted <code>IsLocalizationMap</code> predicate.</p>",
        "id": 535596118,
        "sender_full_name": "Junyan Xu",
        "timestamp": 1755822023
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I found that there are at least two notions of linear independence in use over semirings, and even and expert in the subject matter can get confused. Golan's classic reference <em>Semirings and their Applications</em> (1999) agrees with the current mathlib definition, and in Example (17.7) (only two pages after the definition), Golan claims that B is a linearly-independent subset of M having more than three elements, ostensibly violating the strong rank condition. However if you look into the reference <a href=\"https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0165011488900085\">Guo et al., 1988</a> (Example 2), you see that they use a different notion of linearly independence (each element is not contained in the span of the other elements). This notion is equivalent to the span of individual elements being <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=iSupIndep#doc\">docs#iSupIndep</a>, and could be named LinearIrredundant to avoid the terminology clash.</p>\n<p><a href=\"/user_uploads/3121/Sdry2BsN-j7VfCB_P_RwyzsA/image.png\">Golan: Definition of linear independence</a><br>\n<a href=\"/user_uploads/3121/wSpCshqSChcMNQe-E_p_FJbp/image.png\">Golan: Example (17.7)</a><br>\n<a href=\"/user_uploads/3121/i5VI-_HT8yUF-BE5aYdt7aG9/image.png\">Alternative definition</a></p>\n<div class=\"message_inline_image\"><a href=\"/user_uploads/3121/Sdry2BsN-j7VfCB_P_RwyzsA/image.png\" title=\"Golan: Definition of linear independence\"><img data-original-content-type=\"image/png\" data-original-dimensions=\"924x781\" src=\"/user_uploads/thumbnail/3121/Sdry2BsN-j7VfCB_P_RwyzsA/image.png/840x560.webp\"></a></div><div class=\"message_inline_image\"><a href=\"/user_uploads/3121/wSpCshqSChcMNQe-E_p_FJbp/image.png\" title=\"Golan: Example (17.7)\"><img data-original-content-type=\"image/png\" data-original-dimensions=\"941x374\" src=\"/user_uploads/thumbnail/3121/wSpCshqSChcMNQe-E_p_FJbp/image.png/840x560.webp\"></a></div><div class=\"message_inline_image\"><a href=\"/user_uploads/3121/i5VI-_HT8yUF-BE5aYdt7aG9/image.png\" title=\"Alternative definition\"><img data-original-content-type=\"image/png\" data-original-dimensions=\"933x397\" src=\"/user_uploads/thumbnail/3121/i5VI-_HT8yUF-BE5aYdt7aG9/image.png/840x560.webp\"></a></div><p>A <a href=\"https://doi.org/10.1016/j.laa.2016.02.006\">2016 paper</a> I found yesterday uses the same definition of linear independence, and mathlib's <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=LinearIndependent#doc\">docs#LinearIndependent</a> is called \"free\" there. (Mathlib's <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=Basis#doc\">docs#Basis</a> is called \"free basis\", and <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=Submodule.spanRank#doc\">docs#Submodule.spanRank</a> is called \"rank\".) With this dictionary in mind, Theorem 3.2 of the paper implies that nontrivial commutative semirings satisfy the strong rank condition, answering a <a href=\"https://mathoverflow.net/questions/495394/do-all-commutative-semirings-satisfy-the-strong-rank-condition\">MO question</a> of mine. It looks like the proof depends on 14 pages of the paper plus <a href=\"https://doi.org/10.1016/j.laa.2013.11.024\">an 2013 paper</a> by the same author <del>and a <a href=\"https://doi.org/10.1016/j.laa.2004.02.019\">2004 paper</a></del> (update: all that are needed in this paper seem to be included in <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"253861\">@Thomas Browning</span>'s work in <a href=\"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/pull/19581\">#19581</a>), so it will be a nontrivial effort to formalize the result.</p>\n<p><a href=\"/user_uploads/3121/TJhhfyX2az5nB_UGbG1zs6r2/image.png\">2016 paper: Definitions</a><br>\n<a href=\"/user_uploads/3121/A0YiD8VCsOcjc4Puv9ttXrgZ/image.png\">2016 paper: Theorem 3.2</a></p>\n<div class=\"message_inline_image\"><a href=\"/user_uploads/3121/TJhhfyX2az5nB_UGbG1zs6r2/image.png\" title=\"2016 paper: Definitions\"><img data-original-content-type=\"image/png\" data-original-dimensions=\"1180x604\" src=\"/user_uploads/thumbnail/3121/TJhhfyX2az5nB_UGbG1zs6r2/image.png/840x560.webp\"></a></div><div class=\"message_inline_image\"><a href=\"/user_uploads/3121/A0YiD8VCsOcjc4Puv9ttXrgZ/image.png\" title=\"2016 paper: Theorem 3.2\"><img data-original-content-type=\"image/png\" data-original-dimensions=\"1184x251\" src=\"/user_uploads/thumbnail/3121/A0YiD8VCsOcjc4Puv9ttXrgZ/image.png/840x560.webp\"></a></div>",
        "id": 560251552,
